00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:30.080
OK.

00:39:30.080 --> 00:39:33.460
So, why a uniquely
human perspective?

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:36.230
Because a deeper understanding
builds trust with people

00:39:36.230 --> 00:39:38.780
with autism and their
families, makes our communities

00:39:38.780 --> 00:39:41.690
more humane and caring, and
makes us all better people.

00:39:41.690 --> 00:39:44.670
And Justin's boss at the
time that this video was

00:39:44.670 --> 00:39:48.060
made actually said,
you know, the fact

00:39:48.060 --> 00:39:51.500
that Justin is a great
artist is a "so what" to me.

00:39:51.500 --> 00:39:53.880
The fact that he's an
inspiration to every employee

00:39:53.880 --> 00:39:57.631
of mine is what really counts.

00:39:57.631 --> 00:39:58.130
OK.

00:39:58.130 --> 00:40:01.590
So I think we're OK for some
questions now if you have.

00:40:01.590 --> 00:40:02.090
Yes.

00:40:02.090 --> 00:40:05.024
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about schools and teachers,

00:40:05.024 --> 00:40:07.690
because one of the things that I
see, I'm an education advocate,

00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:11.650
is that the IAPs, they're
almost cookie cutter IAPs

00:40:11.650 --> 00:40:12.980
for each child with autism.

00:40:12.980 --> 00:40:15.370
And it makes me
crazy that they don't

00:40:15.370 --> 00:40:18.070
understand the differences
between the children.

00:40:18.070 --> 00:40:20.020
Can you recommend some
particular websites

00:40:20.020 --> 00:40:22.460
that I can give to
teachers to understand

00:40:22.460 --> 00:40:25.270
that not all people
with autism are alike,

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:27.280
and they don't need the
same accommodations?

00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:30.490
And I'm having a
hard time getting

00:40:30.490 --> 00:40:31.490
them to understand that.

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:33.021
BARRY PRIZANT: Yes.

00:40:33.021 --> 00:40:33.520
Yes.

00:40:33.520 --> 00:40:35.800
The issue-- and that
is an important issue.

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:38.180
There are some approaches--
educational approaches

00:40:38.180 --> 00:40:41.150
in autism-- which
are kind of one size

00:40:41.150 --> 00:40:44.177
fits all for all children.

00:40:44.177 --> 00:40:46.010
We actually have an
educational model that's

00:40:46.010 --> 00:40:47.301
being used in 12 countries now.

00:40:47.301 --> 00:40:48.620
It's highly individualized.

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:51.560
It's a developmentally
based model.

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:54.920
So actually a
colleague of mine who's

00:40:54.920 --> 00:40:58.101
from this area-- Dr. Karen
Levine, who's a psychologist--

00:40:58.101 --> 00:40:58.600
yeah.

00:40:58.600 --> 00:41:00.670
Karen just came out
with a book called

00:41:00.670 --> 00:41:05.310
"Individualized Interventions
for Children with Autism."

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:07.500
I believe it came out last year.

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:11.570
But people are finally
moving away from that.

00:41:11.570 --> 00:41:15.800
Because more traditional
behavioral approaches

00:41:15.800 --> 00:41:18.790
dominated for so many years
based upon operant conditioning

00:41:18.790 --> 00:41:19.910
approaches.

00:41:19.910 --> 00:41:23.690
And if you don't look at
a person-- any person--

00:41:23.690 --> 00:41:27.020
developmentally, you can't
appreciate the learning

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:27.710
differences.

00:41:27.710 --> 00:41:29.180
And you can't
appreciate that you

00:41:29.180 --> 00:41:31.680
have to use different strategies
and very different teaching

00:41:31.680 --> 00:41:34.110
modalities to really
reach this person.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:37.720
I would say that's probably
in my mind, one of the top two

00:41:37.720 --> 00:41:43.200
or three really bad things that
happen to people with autism,

00:41:43.200 --> 00:41:45.890
getting snapped into a
program that is supposed

00:41:45.890 --> 00:41:48.740
to work because you
reinforce the right behaviors

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:50.255
and you use the
right reinforcers.

00:41:50.255 --> 00:41:51.630
But it has nothing
to do with who

00:41:51.630 --> 00:41:55.300
that person is in terms of their
strengths and their interests.

00:41:55.300 --> 00:41:57.020
AUDIENCE: Or the social
pragmatics piece.

00:41:57.020 --> 00:41:59.603
I'll find that like, well, we're
giving him social pragmatics.

00:41:59.603 --> 00:42:01.580
And it's just a
matter of the child--

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:02.830
it's a script for the child.

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:05.760
They can do it during lunch
bunch or what have you.

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.260
But they're not
having opportunities

00:42:07.260 --> 00:42:09.749
to practice it in the real
world, or an assumption

00:42:09.749 --> 00:42:11.790
like, oh well, just because
they have pragmatics,

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:13.097
they're going to learn how to--

00:42:13.097 --> 00:42:14.680
BARRY PRIZANT: For
decades and decades

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:18.380
we've learned that if you
teach a child or a person

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:21.260
with autism something
in one situation,

00:42:21.260 --> 00:42:24.230
and you only measure progress in
that situation, that's not what

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:26.070
we call meaningful progress.

00:42:26.070 --> 00:42:28.590
So I could speak about my
model with my colleagues,

00:42:28.590 --> 00:42:33.300
called ASSERTs model, which we
talk about natural environments

00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:35.010
with the right supports.

00:42:35.010 --> 00:42:38.940
And whenever we talk about
important goals and objectives

00:42:38.940 --> 00:42:41.890
to help a child to be a
more competent communicator,

00:42:41.890 --> 00:42:44.680
it's always
simultaneously approached

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:47.010
across homeschooling
community settings.

00:42:47.010 --> 00:42:48.161
It has to work that way.

00:42:48.161 --> 00:42:49.535
Unfortunately,
the learning style

00:42:49.535 --> 00:42:53.610
of some people with autism
is situation-specific.

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:56.800
So yes, I could learn
to say this or do this

00:42:56.800 --> 00:43:00.210
Monday, Wednesday, Friday
with the speech pathologist

00:43:00.210 --> 00:43:01.630
in this room.

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:03.860
But we have to
build in the ability

00:43:03.860 --> 00:43:05.780
to generalize across
many different settings.

00:43:05.780 --> 00:43:07.554
Yes.

00:43:07.554 --> 00:43:08.095
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:08.095 --> 00:43:10.220
So it was actually nice
to see Justin up there.

00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:10.930
I know him.

00:43:10.930 --> 00:43:11.860
I'm from New Jersey.

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:13.210
I lived right outside Montclair.

00:43:13.210 --> 00:43:14.260
BARRY PRIZANT: Oh my goodness.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:14.885
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:14.885 --> 00:43:17.989
So, my younger
brother has PDNOS.

00:43:17.989 --> 00:43:20.030
BARRY PRIZANT: Which is
no longer a category now.

00:43:20.030 --> 00:43:21.040
AUDIENCE: I know.

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:22.870
So, that's been a
whole other thing.

00:43:22.870 --> 00:43:25.200
I'm trying to work
with that into his IP

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:28.280
and scholastic things,
changes from that.

00:43:28.280 --> 00:43:30.080
But my brother has autism.

00:43:30.080 --> 00:43:32.120
Two of my cousins.

00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:35.640
My grandfather, my
uncle, and my aunt.

00:43:35.640 --> 00:43:41.150
And just seeing the way that my
immediate family has approached

00:43:41.150 --> 00:43:45.460
it as opposed to the
family of my cousins

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:47.380
is completely polar
opposite situations.

00:43:47.380 --> 00:43:51.310
Whereas my cousins' family has
bought more into the Autism

00:43:51.310 --> 00:43:54.570
Speaks dialogue, as
opposed to my family, which

00:43:54.570 --> 00:43:58.420
is trying to-- I do a
lot of advocacy work

00:43:58.420 --> 00:44:00.880
with my brother, who knows
he has autism, and does

00:44:00.880 --> 00:44:04.360
a lot of outreach stuff too.

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:07.330
Trying to institute person-first
language into schools

00:44:07.330 --> 00:44:08.640
and things like that.

00:44:08.640 --> 00:44:13.440
So what would you say is the
best approach, besides reading

00:44:13.440 --> 00:44:16.290
your book and attending
talks like this, to try

00:44:16.290 --> 00:44:18.850
to make people
understand the importance

00:44:18.850 --> 00:44:22.350
of linguistic markers
and things when speaking

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:23.665
about people with autism.

00:44:23.665 --> 00:44:25.040
BARRY PRIZANT:
Well, let me first

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:27.210
address that point right away.

00:44:27.210 --> 00:44:29.700
And I actually do begin
the book with this,

00:44:29.700 --> 00:44:32.140
that I use person-first
language, child with autism,

00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:33.550
person with autism.

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:35.790
I'm not militant about it.

00:44:35.790 --> 00:44:39.500
There are some very
prominent important voices

00:44:39.500 --> 00:44:43.080
in the field of autism-- people
with autism now-- who say, no.

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:44.310
I'm autistic.

00:44:44.310 --> 00:44:47.080
I'd rather you call me
autistic or an autist,

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:49.370
than call me person with
autism, because it's

00:44:49.370 --> 00:44:52.100
such an inherent part
of who I am as a person.

00:44:52.100 --> 00:44:54.340
Temple Grandin says that.

00:44:54.340 --> 00:44:56.730
Temple Grandin refers to people
with autism as autistics.

00:44:56.730 --> 00:44:58.070
OK?

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:00.830
And she says, it's an
inherent part of who I am.

00:45:00.830 --> 00:45:03.960
So I think it really is the
preference of the individual,

00:45:03.960 --> 00:45:05.550
as far as that goes.

00:45:05.550 --> 00:45:09.030
But when you talk about the
Autism Speaks perspective,

00:45:09.030 --> 00:45:11.930
I can imagine most of you are
familiar with Autism Speaks.

00:45:11.930 --> 00:45:14.500
Started by grandparents
of a son with autism.

00:45:14.500 --> 00:45:19.727
He also happened to be at the
time, the CEO of NBC Universal.

00:45:19.727 --> 00:45:22.060
It's the largest advocacy--
quote/unquote-- organization

00:45:22.060 --> 00:45:23.070
in the world.

00:45:23.070 --> 00:45:25.840
And they've been
drifting back towards,

00:45:25.840 --> 00:45:28.900
a little bit towards, let's
really help people with autism

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:29.430
every day.

00:45:29.430 --> 00:45:31.220
Initially it was all about cure.

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:34.900
And the $60, $80 million they
raised a year in research,

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:36.770
the great majority
of it was going

00:45:36.770 --> 00:45:40.020
towards biomedical
research about a cure.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:42.020
And at the same time
this was all happening,

00:45:42.020 --> 00:45:43.790
they had about
80, 100 employees.

00:45:43.790 --> 00:45:45.510
Not one had autism.

00:45:45.510 --> 00:45:49.250
And actually, John Elder
Robertson, whom I quoted,

00:45:49.250 --> 00:45:50.959
was invited to be an employee.

00:45:50.959 --> 00:45:52.500
And he lasted three
months because he

00:45:52.500 --> 00:45:55.350
said he couldn't
tolerate the way they

00:45:55.350 --> 00:45:56.540
looked at autism there.

00:45:56.540 --> 00:45:58.860
But it's the most
powerful organization--

00:45:58.860 --> 00:45:59.609
visibly powerful.

00:45:59.609 --> 00:46:01.900
You know the lighted up blue,
where all these buildings

00:46:01.900 --> 00:46:04.920
all over the world are
lit up blue from Dubai

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:09.560
to the Empire State Building--
they're responsible for that.

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:11.620
They're changing as
the grandson grows,

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:13.350
and they see he's not
going to be cured,

00:46:13.350 --> 00:46:16.290
and as things begin to
shift a little bit more

00:46:16.290 --> 00:46:17.980
towards quality of life.

00:46:17.980 --> 00:46:18.840
But yeah.

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:21.920
When you have very
loud voices kind

00:46:21.920 --> 00:46:24.950
of dominating the
discussion about autism,

00:46:24.950 --> 00:46:27.360
it gets away from there
are other points of view.

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:29.327
Like in your family,
and how do we

00:46:29.327 --> 00:46:31.160
teach people about that
other point of view.

00:46:31.160 --> 00:46:34.430
One of the best ways I say
right now is what I've done.

00:46:34.430 --> 00:46:36.090
Listen to people with autism.

00:46:36.090 --> 00:46:40.100
There are so many voices,
so many people right now,

00:46:40.100 --> 00:46:45.080
so many blogs of extremely
thoughtful, articulate people

00:46:45.080 --> 00:46:48.070
with autism, many
married, have kids.

00:46:48.070 --> 00:46:51.100
But they're very upfront
about their challenges.

00:46:51.100 --> 00:46:53.380
Some who don't wish
ever to be married.

00:46:53.380 --> 00:46:55.660
And they could talk
about that as well.

00:46:55.660 --> 00:47:00.280
But for me, luckily I met
Temple Grandin in the '80s.

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:03.150
And I've hosted her many times
to speak at our conferences.

00:47:03.150 --> 00:47:05.980
So I was exposed to people
with autism early on.

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:09.430
And now I regularly do workshops
with people with autism.

00:47:09.430 --> 00:47:10.140
I'm a sponge.

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:12.720
I just soak up every
bit of understanding

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:14.930
that I can come
from folks who can

00:47:14.930 --> 00:47:17.270
talk about their
first-hand experience.

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:19.020
AUDIENCE: Just a quick
follow-up question.

00:47:19.020 --> 00:47:22.210
Why do you think that research
organizations and people

00:47:22.210 --> 00:47:24.210
as a whole have
been so-- initially

00:47:24.210 --> 00:47:27.050
at least-- adverse to listening
to people who have autism?

00:47:27.050 --> 00:47:29.407
Why has it taken us so
long to get to that point?

00:47:29.407 --> 00:47:30.240
BARRY PRIZANT: Yeah.

00:47:30.240 --> 00:47:31.240
That's a great question.

00:47:31.240 --> 00:47:33.970
Why has it taken so long to
listen to people with autism?

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:37.730
For many years I actually
said, when Temple Grandin

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:39.477
was pretty much the
only voice out there,

00:47:39.477 --> 00:47:42.060
I said, well it's wonderful that
she's sharing her experience.

00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:45.790
But when I see people listen
to her at a conference,

00:47:45.790 --> 00:47:49.810
they're more there because
she's a curiosity then

00:47:49.810 --> 00:47:54.320
are they there to really take
to heart what she's saying.

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:57.460
And I think it's still happens
when professionals are not

00:47:57.460 --> 00:47:59.630
exposed to a lot of
people with autism,

00:47:59.630 --> 00:48:01.297
I think it's like,
oh my goodness.

00:48:01.297 --> 00:48:02.880
This person with
autism could actually

00:48:02.880 --> 00:48:05.740
tell me what their
emotions are like,

00:48:05.740 --> 00:48:07.230
and their inner world is like.

00:48:07.230 --> 00:48:09.860
And we have to get
beyond that curiosity

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:14.010
and say, these are such
important, critical voices

00:48:14.010 --> 00:48:16.210
to help us all understand.

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:19.210
Another reason is that
a lot of what they say

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:23.080
goes against common
practices in the field.

00:48:23.080 --> 00:48:27.540
Like for years, decades, you
had to do eye contact training

00:48:27.540 --> 00:48:28.797
for people with autism.

00:48:28.797 --> 00:48:30.630
And now you have dozens
of articulate people

00:48:30.630 --> 00:48:33.204
with autism saying, you
know, it's really hard for me

00:48:33.204 --> 00:48:35.120
to process what you're
saying when you make me

00:48:35.120 --> 00:48:37.020
look at you at the same time.

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:41.050
And so they're actually
shaming, in some ways,

00:48:41.050 --> 00:48:43.881
a lot of very well-known people
in the field in education

00:48:43.881 --> 00:48:45.630
and treatment, because
what they're saying

00:48:45.630 --> 00:48:48.050
is the opposite of
what these people have

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:49.860
prescribed for so many years.

00:48:49.860 --> 00:48:52.290
So I think there's a little
bit of that element as well.

00:48:52.290 --> 00:48:54.123
As a matter of fact, a
number of years ago--

00:48:54.123 --> 00:48:57.040
and this happened in Boston
at one of the schools for kids

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.749
with autism-- there was
a very well-known woman

00:48:59.749 --> 00:49:01.040
who has now written five books.

00:49:01.040 --> 00:49:01.770
Donna Williams.

00:49:01.770 --> 00:49:02.790
She's from Australia.

00:49:02.790 --> 00:49:04.180
She has autism.

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:06.540
And she was coming to
speak in New England.

00:49:06.540 --> 00:49:09.240
And she speaks very much
against the type of approach

00:49:09.240 --> 00:49:11.760
that was used in this
school in the Boston area.

00:49:11.760 --> 00:49:14.229
And people sent out all these
faxes saying, she's a phony.

00:49:14.229 --> 00:49:15.520
She really doesn't have autism.

00:49:15.520 --> 00:49:17.090
Don't listen to her.

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:18.650
And it's kind of
like, people just

00:49:18.650 --> 00:49:21.170
couldn't tolerate
that she was a voice

00:49:21.170 --> 00:49:26.900
speaking against the approach
that was used at this school.

00:49:26.900 --> 00:49:30.469
Heavy duty politics
in the field.

00:49:30.469 --> 00:49:31.010
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:49:31.010 --> 00:49:31.759
BARRY PRIZANT: Hi.

00:49:31.759 --> 00:49:33.460
AUDIENCE: I'm a
speech therapist.

00:49:33.460 --> 00:49:35.910
And what I've noticed
is that the schools

00:49:35.910 --> 00:49:39.260
are very eager to give out
behavioral supports-- 20

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:42.060
hours of ABA for
our little kids--

00:49:42.060 --> 00:49:45.720
and not so eager to
give out speech therapy.

00:49:45.720 --> 00:49:52.820
How does that-- all the
enthusiasm towards ABA,

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:54.900
shape, you know,
what you're talking

00:49:54.900 --> 00:49:58.450
about in terms of behavior
and how we look at it.

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:03.160
And what should we do
to use them, and use

00:50:03.160 --> 00:50:05.426
that support to our benefit?

00:50:05.426 --> 00:50:08.660
BARRY PRIZANT: Do we have
time for a full day workshop?

00:50:08.660 --> 00:50:11.730
First of all, let me just
say, when we talk about ABA

00:50:11.730 --> 00:50:13.800
applied behavior
analysis, there are

00:50:13.800 --> 00:50:15.420
about eight different versions.

00:50:15.420 --> 00:50:16.080
OK?

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:18.790
There's very traditional ABA,
which we speak up against.

00:50:18.790 --> 00:50:20.810
And that's set the
child down and drill

00:50:20.810 --> 00:50:22.410
and drill over and over again.

00:50:22.410 --> 00:50:24.750
Train eye contact, and so forth.

00:50:24.750 --> 00:50:28.460
There are many very
fine behavior analysts

00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:31.720
who have taken in some of
the developmental literature,

00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:35.200
and the individual
learning style literature.

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:38.244
And actually, I like to say
there are some folks in ABA who

00:50:38.244 --> 00:50:39.660
are closer to what
we do than they

00:50:39.660 --> 00:50:41.660
are to other people within ABA.

00:50:41.660 --> 00:50:42.220
OK?

00:50:42.220 --> 00:50:43.530
So there's been a shift.

00:50:43.530 --> 00:50:47.340
This area, in particular,
Massachusetts.

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:51.150
New Jersey is another state
very heavily influenced by ABA.

00:50:51.150 --> 00:50:53.220
Other places in the
country, not so much.

00:50:53.220 --> 00:50:56.050
There definitely is a shift
and an change that's happening.

00:50:56.050 --> 00:50:58.150
And I could talk to you
about this afterwards.

00:50:58.150 --> 00:51:00.850
But actually our organization--
the American Speech Language

00:51:00.850 --> 00:51:05.660
Hearing Association--
just successfully filed

00:51:05.660 --> 00:51:08.860
a formal complaint to the
Federal Department of Education

00:51:08.860 --> 00:51:11.680
about ABA having
too much influence,

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:14.660
especially in teaching
language and communication.

00:51:14.660 --> 00:51:16.160
And the Department
of Education just

00:51:16.160 --> 00:51:18.500
released a letter
last month saying,

00:51:18.500 --> 00:51:21.220
we need to have all
disciplines involved.

00:51:21.220 --> 00:51:24.890
And that basically applied
behavior analysts are not

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:27.530
the specialists in
all areas in autism.

00:51:27.530 --> 00:51:30.010
So people are now
saying, wait a second.

00:51:30.010 --> 00:51:32.750
That is, I believe
this down to my core.

00:51:32.750 --> 00:51:34.630
A team approach is best.

00:51:34.630 --> 00:51:37.690
When you have OT speech
and language pathologists,

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:42.460
educators, parents, behavior
analysts all working together,

00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:44.960
and you don't have a
hierarchy of one person who's

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:46.210
calling all the shots.

00:51:46.210 --> 00:51:48.860
And unfortunately,
that creates all kinds

00:51:48.860 --> 00:51:50.470
of problems when I
go to schools and I

00:51:50.470 --> 00:51:52.170
see that hierarchy in place.

00:51:52.170 --> 00:51:55.400
It really needs to
be a team approach.

00:51:55.400 --> 00:51:57.150
And I want to emphasize
the parents having

00:51:57.150 --> 00:51:58.100
a very strong voice.

00:52:01.004 --> 00:52:03.860
AUDIENCE: I just wanted
to ask about linking

00:52:03.860 --> 00:52:07.490
to humor, sort of making a
cognitive basis for humor.

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:11.140
And how if you've
worked with that

00:52:11.140 --> 00:52:13.250
in your particular practice.

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:16.730
It seems like five years
ago, very few people

00:52:16.730 --> 00:52:18.040
were talking about it.

00:52:18.040 --> 00:52:20.850
If I Google it now, I
get lots of results.

00:52:20.850 --> 00:52:23.070
And I wondered if you
could address that.

00:52:23.070 --> 00:52:25.850
BARRY PRIZANT: Well, in
a way, the whole issue

00:52:25.850 --> 00:52:29.030
of humor and autism
makes as discard one

00:52:29.030 --> 00:52:32.670
of the kind of a
longstanding false beliefs,

00:52:32.670 --> 00:52:35.070
that people with autism
don't have a sense of humor.

00:52:35.070 --> 00:52:38.090
They have a different
sense of humor, OK?

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:40.720
So people with autism
might find humor

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:45.630
in word meanings or wordplay,
but not necessarily humor

00:52:45.630 --> 00:52:49.070
that's deeply embedded in
social nuance, if you will,

00:52:49.070 --> 00:52:50.250
in some cases.

00:52:50.250 --> 00:52:54.040
But there's actually a project
down at the Groden Center

00:52:54.040 --> 00:52:59.440
in Providence that's led
by-- oh my goodness-- Cooper

00:52:59.440 --> 00:53:01.360
Woodard, who's a psychologist.

00:53:01.360 --> 00:53:03.260
And it's a positive
psychology approach

00:53:03.260 --> 00:53:05.890
to autism, where they teach
the students with autism

00:53:05.890 --> 00:53:10.826
to tell jokes, and to engage
in activities that-- and I'm

00:53:10.826 --> 00:53:12.700
going to move a little
bit off of humor now--

00:53:12.700 --> 00:53:15.230
but that create
positive emotion, shared

00:53:15.230 --> 00:53:17.447
positive emotional experiences.

00:53:17.447 --> 00:53:19.030
But once you get
into humor, if you're

00:53:19.030 --> 00:53:21.540
talking about humor
through language,

00:53:21.540 --> 00:53:23.649
then that could be
challenging for some people

00:53:23.649 --> 00:53:24.315
on the spectrum.

00:53:25.380 --> 00:53:27.390
One of the things that's
really fascinating

00:53:27.390 --> 00:53:31.080
is people with autism
often find humor

00:53:31.080 --> 00:53:34.930
through nonverbal
behavior really engaging.

00:53:34.930 --> 00:53:38.380
So for example, looking
at old silent movies,

00:53:38.380 --> 00:53:40.800
or I'm going to
blank on this now,

00:53:40.800 --> 00:53:46.990
but there's a comedian, English
comedian, and some of his work

00:53:46.990 --> 00:53:48.840
has been on PBS over the years.

00:53:48.840 --> 00:53:50.240
And it's almost mime-like.

00:53:50.240 --> 00:53:51.780
It's purely nonverbal.

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:53.610
And a lot of people
with autism just

00:53:53.610 --> 00:53:56.900
find his humor to be the
funniest humor in the world,

00:53:56.900 --> 00:54:00.519
because in a sense, it dances
the linguistic aspect of it.

00:54:00.519 --> 00:54:01.060
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:54:01.060 --> 00:54:05.130
Our son has been
diagnosed on the spectrum.

00:54:05.130 --> 00:54:08.360
Very low, when he was
treated when he was six.

00:54:08.360 --> 00:54:09.500
He's now 11.

00:54:09.500 --> 00:54:13.730
And we have chosen not
to have an IAP for him.

00:54:13.730 --> 00:54:17.170
And usually we end up
working with the teachers

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:18.500
and meeting with them.

00:54:18.500 --> 00:54:20.830
Invariably they contact us.

00:54:20.830 --> 00:54:23.110
And it's like, we
need to have sit down.

00:54:23.110 --> 00:54:26.960
Well, next year he's going to
have more than two teachers.

00:54:26.960 --> 00:54:29.180
And there's gonna be
about seven of them.

00:54:29.180 --> 00:54:33.530
And I don't think this approach
is going to work anymore.

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:35.930
Is there something
you can suggest?

00:54:35.930 --> 00:54:40.730
I mean, I agree with the IAP
not being the best route.

00:54:40.730 --> 00:54:43.966
But next year we won't
be able to sit down

00:54:43.966 --> 00:54:45.260
with seven teachers.

00:54:45.260 --> 00:54:46.190
BARRY PRIZANT: Right.

00:54:46.190 --> 00:54:47.350
Yeah.

00:54:47.350 --> 00:54:50.625
And you know, unfortunately
for the challenge

00:54:50.625 --> 00:54:52.640
you're facing, if
you would ask me

00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:56.090
what is one of the best
situations for a student

00:54:56.090 --> 00:54:58.510
or a child with autism,
educational situations,

00:54:58.510 --> 00:55:01.050
it's when everybody's
on the same page.

00:55:01.050 --> 00:55:04.410
And it's less confusing, be
less confusing to your child,

00:55:04.410 --> 00:55:05.896
and less confusing to you.

00:55:08.630 --> 00:55:10.570
Without knowing specifics,
it's hard for me

00:55:10.570 --> 00:55:12.910
to make any specific
suggestions.

00:55:12.910 --> 00:55:16.257
I will tell you this, that
one of my earliest experiences

00:55:16.257 --> 00:55:17.840
that was such a
wonderful experience--

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:22.180
and I'm not saying you need
to do this-- was a family who

00:55:22.180 --> 00:55:24.580
had many different people
both in and out of school

00:55:24.580 --> 00:55:26.020
working with their son.

00:55:26.020 --> 00:55:28.760
And he was 10 or 11 at the time.

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:33.080
And what they did
was once a month,

00:55:33.080 --> 00:55:35.810
they would have a potluck
dinner over at their house

00:55:35.810 --> 00:55:38.640
and invite everybody over
as a way for everybody

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:40.804
to relate to each
other, and truly feel

00:55:40.804 --> 00:55:41.970
that they're part of a team.

00:55:41.970 --> 00:55:44.090
That's going to be
your major challenge,

00:55:44.090 --> 00:55:46.310
that people feel
connected to each other

00:55:46.310 --> 00:55:48.290
to share information.

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:52.721
And so we can all be on
the same page for your son.

00:55:52.721 --> 00:55:54.970
But if you have people coming
from different practices

00:55:54.970 --> 00:55:57.178
and some from private practice
and so forth, again, I

00:55:57.178 --> 00:56:00.710
don't know the specifics
of your situation, what's

00:56:00.710 --> 00:56:02.770
going to be so important
for you to reinforce

00:56:02.770 --> 00:56:05.440
is that we are part of the team.

00:56:05.440 --> 00:56:09.240
And certainly
using-- whether it's

00:56:09.240 --> 00:56:11.395
bulletin boards, message
boards on the internet--

00:56:11.395 --> 00:56:13.640
and they do have ones
that can be secure now,

00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:16.310
where everybody could
communicate with each other,

00:56:16.310 --> 00:56:19.370
and talk about, well, what
just worked in this activity,

00:56:19.370 --> 00:56:21.940
or what we're shifting
out some other goals

00:56:21.940 --> 00:56:24.050
that we're adopting,
and so forth.

00:56:24.050 --> 00:56:26.980
AUDIENCE: Do you find it
useful to proactively speak

00:56:26.980 --> 00:56:29.530
to the teachers,
speak to them prior

00:56:29.530 --> 00:56:33.670
to the school year starting?

00:56:33.670 --> 00:56:35.470
You know, in that respect?

00:56:35.470 --> 00:56:36.830
BARRY PRIZANT: Absolutely.

00:56:36.830 --> 00:56:40.470
And you know, that's
referred to by some people

00:56:40.470 --> 00:56:42.210
as transition planning.

00:56:42.210 --> 00:56:44.794
And it's actually some of what
I do when I consult to schools.

00:56:44.794 --> 00:56:47.251
When I consult to schools on
a regular basis, and I go back

00:56:47.251 --> 00:56:48.300
and I know the people.

00:56:48.300 --> 00:56:50.840
We start transition
planning for some kids

00:56:50.840 --> 00:56:53.470
as early as April
of the school year

00:56:53.470 --> 00:56:55.890
before, planning for September.

00:56:55.890 --> 00:56:57.390
Who's going to be the teacher.

00:56:57.390 --> 00:57:00.800
What visual supports do we want
to have to go with the child.

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:05.550
And in best-case
scenario, we have

00:57:05.550 --> 00:57:10.040
staff from the coming year come
to observe the student now,

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:12.230
before the transition happens.

00:57:12.230 --> 00:57:14.830
The more we can make
things predictable--

00:57:14.830 --> 00:57:17.140
not only for a
child with autism--

00:57:17.140 --> 00:57:20.800
but for all of the
staff, the better

00:57:20.800 --> 00:57:23.710
it will be come September
or August, whenever

00:57:23.710 --> 00:57:25.560
the school year starts for you.

00:57:25.560 --> 00:57:26.790
So that's important.

00:57:26.790 --> 00:57:29.950
It's also important
to build trust.

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:32.600
We speak a lot about
professionals and parents

00:57:32.600 --> 00:57:34.650
building trust
together in my book.

00:57:34.650 --> 00:57:38.200
And that is so important,
because as you probably know,

00:57:38.200 --> 00:57:39.850
sometimes it goes the other way.

00:57:39.850 --> 00:57:41.880
And you begin to have
adversarial relationships

00:57:41.880 --> 00:57:43.080
and mistrust.

00:57:43.080 --> 00:57:45.071
And unfortunately,
in many cases,

00:57:45.071 --> 00:57:46.445
it's the family
and the child who

00:57:46.445 --> 00:57:48.290
are the victims of
that when it happens.

00:57:48.290 --> 00:57:50.810
There are some very, very
fine professionals also

00:57:50.810 --> 00:57:53.560
who will bend over
backwards for you.

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:56.216
And those are the people
to-- they're golden.

00:57:56.216 --> 00:57:57.840
AUDIENCE: Just two
suggestions for you.

00:57:57.840 --> 00:58:00.650
One of the things you can do
is like, think outside the box.

00:58:00.650 --> 00:58:02.680
You can contact the
school and ask them

00:58:02.680 --> 00:58:05.679
if they can provide a buddy from
the middle school for someone

00:58:05.679 --> 00:58:06.720
to walk around with them.

00:58:06.720 --> 00:58:08.290
The other thing
you can do is ask

00:58:08.290 --> 00:58:10.980
if your child can visit the
school beforehand, and see

00:58:10.980 --> 00:58:15.479
who the teachers are, just to
help with the comfort level.

00:58:15.479 --> 00:58:17.520
BARRY PRIZANT: Good parts
of transition planning.

00:58:17.520 --> 00:58:18.650
So thank you very much.

00:58:18.650 --> 00:58:19.510
We are out of time.

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:21.790
And I hope this was interesting
and helpful for you.

00:58:21.790 --> 00:58:22.390
Thanks.

00:58:22.390 --> 00:58:25.140
[APPLAUSE]

